{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637538"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0,0.91,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78224"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10382"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10480"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78224"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary active transport is a fundamental cellular process that maintains essential concentration gradients across cell membranes. The sodium-potassium ATPase pump exemplifies this process in all human cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes primary active transport?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Movement of molecules down their concentration gradient","Transport of molecules through membrane channels","Exchange of ions without energy input","Direct use of ATP to move molecules against their concentration gradient","Use of existing ion gradients to transport molecules"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect use of ATP to move molecules against their concentration gradient\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of primary active transport. This process requires the hydrolysis of ATP to provide the energy needed to transport molecules from an area of low concentration to an area of high concentration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of molecules down their concentration gradient\u003C/strong\u003E describes simple diffusion or facilitated diffusion, where molecules naturally move from areas of high to low concentration without requiring energy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport of molecules through membrane channels\u003C/strong\u003E describes facilitated diffusion, which allows specific molecules to pass through protein channels along their concentration gradient\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchange of ions without energy input\u003C/strong\u003E describes facilitated diffusion through antiporter channels, which does not require ATP hydrolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse of existing ion gradients to transport molecules\u003C/strong\u003E describes secondary active transport, which utilises the energy stored in ion gradients previously established by primary active transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium-potassium ATPase pump is a classic example of primary active transport, using ATP to maintain crucial ion gradients by pumping sodium out of the cell while bringing potassium in, both against their concentration gradients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary active transport uses ATP hydrolysis to move molecules against their concentration gradient.","The sodium-potassium ATPase pump is a key example of primary active transport that maintains cellular membrane potential.","Primary active transport differs from secondary active transport which uses existing ion gradients rather than direct ATP hydrolysis."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:47:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:48:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10382"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78224"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam